Colonel '''Charles Edward''' ("'''Chuck'''") '''Jones''' (November 4, 1952 &ndash; September 11, 2001) was a United States Air Force officer, a [[computer programmer]], and an astronaut in the USAF [[Manned Spaceflight Engineer Program]].

==Biography==
[[File:12.6.11CharlesEdwardJonesPanelN-74ByLuigiNovi1.jpg|thumb|left|Jones' name is located on Panel N-74 of the [[National September 11 Memorial]]â€™s North Pool, along with those of other passengers of Flight 11.]]
Jones was born in [[Clinton, Indiana|Clinton]], [[Indiana]].  He graduated from [[Wichita High School East]] in 1970 and earned a bachelor of science in astronautical engineering from the [[United States Air Force Academy]] in 1974. He entered the USAF Manned Spaceflight Engineer program in 1982, and was scheduled to fly on mission [[Cancelled Shuttle missions|STS-71-B]] in December 1986, but the mission was cancelled after the [[Space Shuttle Challenger|''Challenger'' Disaster]] in January 1986. He left the Manned Spaceflight Engineer program in 1987.

He was killed at the age of 48 in the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|attacks of September 11, 2001]], aboard [[American Airlines Flight 11]]. He had been living as a retired [[US Air Force]] Colonel in [[Bedford, Massachusetts|Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]], at the time of his death. He was survived by his wife Jeanette.

At the [[National 9/11 Memorial]], Jones is memorialized at the North Pool, on Panel N-74.<ref>[http://names.911memorial.org/#lang=en_US&page=person&id=4423 Charles Edward Jones]. Memorial Guide: [[National 9/11 Memorial]]. Retrieved December 11, 2011.</ref>{{-}}

